I will explain the app again in detail, so please remember it as " AI LEARNING."

Problem Statement:

1. Unknown- Unknown:
When a user wants to learn anything online—whether through YouTube, websites, or courses—they often encounter a common issue, which I refer to as the “unknown-unknown.” This term describes things they are unaware of even existing, or in other words, the knowledge or skills they don’t realize they need to learn.

Example: Suppose a user wants to learn programming but doesn’t know that tools like VS Code, Vibe Coding, GitHub, or various frameworks exist. How can they learn about these tools if they are unaware of their existence? This lack of awareness makes it challenging for them to find specific courses or videos on the subject. The “unknown-unknown” significantly delays the user’s journey to a comprehensive understanding of what they need to learn, much like an index in a book reveals its contents. Unfortunately, such guidance is often lacking on the internet.

1. The Data filtering :
Even when learners grasp some concepts, common questions arise: Where should I start? Will this video/course cover everything I need? Is this video/course sufficient? Which video should I choose between these two?

There is a wealth of information available online about virtually any topic, and with multiple perspectives and reviews, it can be challenging for users to discern which sources are better, accurate, precise, and sufficient. Many users struggle to navigate the internet or YouTube to find the best content suited to their needs.

Often, a user may watch a particular video only to realize that it did not cover all aspects of the syllabus required, leaving some topics unaddressed. This lack of knowledge and understanding in the field leads to a prevalent issue:  making it difficult for users to determine what is correct and what is not.

1. The Unorganized Data:
Even when users receive a roadmap or syllabus outlining what to watch, the available videos, data, and courses are often disorganized. Users find themselves navigating multiple websites, various YouTube channels, and countless videos from different sources. The information they need is scattered across the internet, with no centralized location for storing all relevant data. Additionally, the content is not presented in a sequential manner, which would allow users to follow along step by step. There is no personalized space for users, forcing them to repeatedly search the internet for information.

4.UnTracking Progress :

When users learn something, they often lack a way to see how far they’ve come and what still needs to be accomplished. There is no mechanism to assess their improvements, strengths, or areas for growth. Consequently, users cannot evaluate the quality of their work, how much they’ve truly grasped, or their depth of understanding in various subjects. It’s common for users to be unsure whether they have fully comprehended what they’ve learned or if the information is merely stored in their heads. This leaves them questioning how well they understand the subject matter.

LEARNIFIY*

An app that organizes the unstructured knowledge on the internet, personalizing it according to the user’s requirements, level, and field of study.

While many AI tools do parts of this (summarizing videos or generating text plans), an app that holistically acts as a “Curriculum Architect”—building a complete, verify-and-click syllabus from the open web

“Spotify of Education.” Just as Spotify didn’t create music but organized it into playlists, this app doesn’t need to create content; it just needs to organize the world’s fragmented free content into “albums” (courses).

This is the difference between a library (Google) and a University Professor (Learnify).

Filter “A Deep Course” || a compilation of videos (these are the two options available in the app)

A Deep Course:
This app divides the entire process of course generation into 4 parts.
Understanding the user, creating a roadmap, organizing the data, and tracking the user’s process.

1. Understanding:
The app will first assess the user’s learning objectives, including the field of study, the desired depth of knowledge—whether a basic overview or in-depth exploration—and the preferred course duration, language, and detail. Additionally, it will inquire whether the user prefers online paid courses, free options, or learning through YouTube. The app will also consider if the user likes to read documents and research papers, or if they wish to take tests upon completing specific chapters. Lastly, it will establish the level of expertise the user aims to achieve, whether that be expert, master, or extreme. This information will equip the app to tailor its offerings to meet the user’s requirements effectively.

(Now, all of the upcoming parts are very similar to Perplexity, and you can assume it will work very similarly to it, but in our own way.)

